-- Oil Gains on Jobs Numbers, Gold Rebounds: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C o l i n   M c C l e l l a n d
-- 2012-04-05T21:48:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-05/oil-gains-on-jobs-numbers-gold-rebounds-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities gained 0.83 percent to 689.14 at 4:13 p.m.  New
York  time. The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials rose
0.58 percent to 1,602.056. U.S. commodity exchanges will be
closed tomorrow for the Good Friday holiday.  CRUDE OIL  Oil gained for the first time in three days as claims for
U.S. unemployment benefits dropped to a four-year low and
equities pared losses, raising hopes that demand will grow in
the world’s leading user of crude.  Crude for May delivery gained $1.84 to settle at $103.31 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Prices rose 29 cents
this week.  Brent oil for May settlement rose $1.09, or 0.9 percent, to
$123.43 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures Europe
exchange. Brent’s premium to WTI narrowed 75 cents to $20.12 a
barrel after widening for six days in a row.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold rose from a 12-week low as  Spain ’s escalating debt
woes spurred demand for a haven. Silver also rebounded  Gold futures for June delivery gained 1 percent to settle
at $1,630.10 an ounce at 1:41 p.m. on the Comex in New York.
Yesterday, the price touched $1,613, the lowest for a most-
active contract since Jan. 10.  Silver futures for May delivery jumped 2.2 percent to
$31.73 an ounce. The price tumbled 6.7 percent yesterday,
touching a 10-week low.  On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum futures for
July delivery rose 0.6 percent to $1,607.60 an ounce. Palladium
futures for June delivery advanced 1.9 percent to $644.80 an
ounce on the Nymex.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline rose after benchmark West Texas Intermediate crude
gained for the first time in three days.  Gasoline for May delivery rose 0.69 cent to settle at
$3.3405 on the Nymex. The fuel has increased 24 percent this
year, making it the best-performing of 24 commodities in the
Standard & Poor’s GSCI index. The contract was down 1.5 percent
this week, the first decline in nine weeks.  Regular gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide, rose 0.8
cent yesterday to $3.936, according to AAA, the nation’s biggest
motoring club. Prices have gained 20 percent this year, and are
6.8 percent above a year ago.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures closed at a 10-year low, capping a
third-straight week of declines, after a government report
showed an above-average increase in U.S. stockpiles as mild
weather crimped demand.  Gas fell 2.4 percent after the Energy Department said
inventories rose 42 billion cubic feet last week to 2.479
trillion. Analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg showed an
expected gain of 34 billion. The five-year increase is 8
billion. Supplies of the heating fuel were 61 percent above
average for the week, the biggest gap in six years.  Natural gas for May delivery declined 5.2 cents to $2.089
per million British thermal units on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange , the lowest settlement price since Jan. 30, 2002. The
futures fell 1.7 percent this week and have dropped 30 percent
this year.  BASE METALS  Copper climbed for the first time in three days as reports
showing an improving labor market and rising consumer confidence
added to signs of recovery in the U.S., the world’s second-
biggest consumer of the metal.  Copper futures for May delivery rose 0.1 percent to settle
at $3.7955 a pound at 1:20 p.m. on the Comex in New York.
Yesterday, the metal slid the most since Dec. 14 after the
 Federal Reserve  damped expectations for more economic stimulus.  Markets reopened in  China , the world’s largest copper
consumer, after closing for a holiday the prior three sessions.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months advanced 0.1 percent to $8,361 a metric ton ($3.79 a
pound).  Aluminum, zinc, lead, tin and nickel also gained in London.  The U.S. and London exchanges will be closed tomorrow for
public holidays, and the LME will be shut on April 9.  GRAINS  Soybeans advanced, rising for the second week, on
speculation that smaller South American harvests will spur
demand for U.S. inventories. Corn gained.  Soybean futures for May delivery gained 1 percent to close
at $14.34 a bushel at 1:15 p.m. on the Chicago Board of Trade.
The oilseed advanced 2.2 percent this week. The commodity has
advanced 19 percent this year after hot, dry weather cut yields
in Brazil and Argentina, the biggest growers after the U.S.  Corn futures for May delivery climbed 0.2 percent to
$6.5825 a bushel in  Chicago . The prices increased 2.2 percent
this week, snapping a two-week decline. The CBOT will be closed
tomorrow for a public holiday.  Wheat fell for a second day as rainfall boosted crop
prospects in the southern U.S. Great Plains and on signs that
freezing weather won’t threaten crops.  Wheat futures for May delivery dropped 0.1 percent to
$6.385 a bushel at 1:15 p.m. on the Chicago Board of Trade. The
price has declined this year on forecasts from the  U.S.
Department of Agriculture  that global stockpiles will rise 5.1
percent to a record 209.6 million tons by the end of the season
on May 31.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Orange-juice futures fell, extending a slump to a five-
month low, on signs of ample supplies. Coffee and cotton
dropped, while cocoa and sugar rose.  Orange juice  for May delivery declined 1.2 percent to
$1.587 a pound at 2 p.m. on ICE Futures U.S. in New York.
Earlier, the price touched $1.5505, the lowest for a most-active
contract since Oct. 10. The commodity has slumped 30 percent
from the all-time high of $2.2695 on Jan. 23.  Arabica-coffee futures for May delivery slid 0.9 percent to
close at $1.83 a pound in New York.  Cotton futures for May delivery fell 0.9 percent to 88.54
cents a pound on ICE.  Also in New York, raw-sugar futures for July delivery
climbed 0.7 percent to close at 23.7 cents a pound. Cocoa
futures for May delivery rose 0.1 percent to $2,085 a ton.  LIVESTOCK  Hogs climbed on speculation that U.S. demand is rebounding
after pork prices slumped to a 15 month-low. Cattle rose.  Hog futures for June settlement gained 1.7 percent to
settle at 93.525 cents a pound at 1 p.m. on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. The commodity has increased 11 percent this
year.  U.S. meatpackers processed an estimated 1.7 million hogs
this week, up 1.2 percent from a week earlier, government data
show.  Cattle futures for June delivery advanced 0.6 percent to
settle at $1.15825 a pound in Chicago. The commodity has dropped
4.6 percent this year.  Feeder-cattle futures for May settlement gained 0.2 percent
to $1.5095 a pound in Chicago.  To contact the reporter on this story:
